
-- HYGIENE - DEFIANT: Refuses to wash hands
INSERT INTO scripts (
  title, category, profile, age_min, age_max,
  the_situation, what_doesnt_work, strategy_steps, why_this_works,
  what_to_expect, common_variations, parent_state_needed, tags, emergency_suitable
) VALUES (
  'Refuses to wash hands - runs away after using bathroom',
  'Hygiene', 'DEFIANT', 3, 9,
  
  'Your DEFIANT child finishes using the bathroom and **bolts**—they run straight past the sink, ignoring your "Wash your hands!" completely. If you chase them or physically guide them back, they twist away, scream "I already did!", or have a full meltdown. This happens **every single time** they use the bathroom, turning basic hygiene into an exhausting battle. You''re caught between forcing it (which feels awful and rarely works) and giving up (which makes you feel like a failure as a parent). You know the germs are spreading, but the power struggle is draining you.',

  '**"Go wash your hands RIGHT NOW or no screen time!"** → Threat creates resistance. Now they MUST refuse to prove you can''t control their body.

**Lecturing about germs and sickness:** "You''ll get sick! Germs will make you throw up!" → Future consequences mean nothing to young DEFIANT brains. They don''t care about getting sick next week—they care about winning the control battle RIGHT NOW.

**Physically dragging them to the sink** → Creates trauma around hygiene and intensifies their need to fight back. The power struggle escalates.

**Giving up after they refuse 3 times** → They learn: "If I fight hard enough, I win." Defiance becomes their most powerful tool.

**Why these don''t work:**
The DEFIANT brain interprets "Wash your hands" as *"I''m controlling your body."* Their refusal is a **neurological response** to perceived loss of autonomy, not stubbornness. Traditional approaches (threats, lectures, force, giving up) all feed the power struggle, making them more determined to resist.',

  '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Pre-bathroom routine: Announce the non-negotiable system","explanation":"BEFORE they use the bathroom (during calm moments), you establish the **routine as reality**, not a request:\n\n→ **\\\"In our house, bathroom means: pee/poop, flush, wash hands, dry hands. That''s how bathrooms work.\\\"**\n\nYou say this with the same neutral tone you''d use to say \\\"Red lights mean stop.\\\" You are NOT asking for cooperation—you''re stating a fact about how bathrooms function in your home.\n\nThen you add the choice element: **\\\"You can wash with soap that smells like strawberries OR soap that smells like lemon. Your choice.\\\"**\n\nThe DEFIANT brain needs to feel this is an **immovable reality** (like gravity), not Mom/Dad''s arbitrary rule they can fight.","example_phrases":["\\\"Bathroom routine: flush, wash hands, dry. That''s how it works in our house.\\\"","\\\"You choose: strawberry soap or lemon soap?\\\"","\\\"Bathroom always includes hand washing. Which soap do you want today?\\\""]},{"step_number":2,"title":"The bathroom door stays locked until completion","explanation":"Here''s the key: the **bathroom door becomes the enforcer**, not you.\n\nYou install a simple hook-and-eye latch or child lock on the OUTSIDE of the bathroom door (high up where they can''t reach). When they finish using the toilet, you calmly say:\n\n→ **\\\"Door stays closed until the routine is done: flush, wash, dry. When you''re finished, you can come out.\\\"**\n\nIf they try to leave without washing: **\\\"Routine''s not done yet. Wash your hands, then the door opens.\\\"**\n\nYou stand outside the door (calm, not angry) and wait. The door is the boundary—not you. This removes the personal power struggle. You''re not MAKING them wash—the door just doesn''t open until the routine is complete.\n\nNOTE: This only works if the bathroom is safe (no dangerous items, child can reach sink). You stay RIGHT outside the door.","example_phrases":["\\\"Routine first, then door opens. Flush, wash, dry.\\\"","\\\"I''ll wait right here. When your hands are clean, you can come out.\\\"","\\\"Door opens when the bathroom routine is finished.\\\""]},{"step_number":3,"title":"Natural consequence: Activities require clean hands","explanation":"If they somehow bypass the door system or refuse to complete the routine, you implement the **natural consequence** calmly:\n\n→ **\\\"You didn''t wash your hands, so you can''t [eat snack / use tablet / touch toys] until your hands are clean.\\\"**\n\nThis is NOT punishment—it''s reality. Dirty hands don''t get to touch food, screens, or shared items. You say this with the same neutral tone you''d use to say \\\"Wet shoes don''t go on the couch.\\\"\n\nIf they rage: **\\\"I know you''re upset. When your hands are clean, you can have your snack.\\\"** Then you wait calmly. The consequence stands.\n\nOver time, most DEFIANT kids realize: Washing hands takes 20 seconds but fighting takes 20 minutes and they STILL have to wash them. They choose cooperation to regain autonomy.","example_phrases":["\\\"Hands need to be clean before you eat. Let''s wash them now.\\\"","\\\"Dirty hands can''t use the tablet. Clean hands can.\\\"","\\\"I''ll wait. When your hands are clean, you can play.\\\""]}]'::jsonb,

  '**Neurologically, DEFIANT children have:**
• **Hyperactive amygdala** (perceives hygiene rules as threats to their bodily autonomy)
• **Underdeveloped prefrontal cortex** (can''t connect "dirty hands now" with "sickness later")
• **Intense need for control** (their brain MUST feel in charge of their own body)

When you say "Wash your hands," their brain hears: *"I''m taking control of your body."* The refusal is a **survival response**, not defiance.

**This strategy works because:**
1. **Pre-teaching the routine** → Frames hand washing as reality (like flushing), not Mom/Dad''s rule to fight
2. **Door as enforcer** → Removes you from the power struggle (door controls exit, not you)
3. **Natural consequences** → Clean hands = access to activities. Dirty hands = wait. No debate, no anger, just reality.

You''re teaching: *"The routine is non-negotiable (like gravity), but you have choices within it (which soap, when to comply). Fighting the routine means you lose access to things you want."*

The resistance stops when cooperation becomes the **path to more autonomy** (faster access to snacks/screens/play), not less.',

  '{"first_30_seconds":"When you first implement the door system, they may scream, bang on the door, or demand to be let out immediately. Stay calm outside the door and repeat: \\\"Routine first, then door opens. Wash your hands.\\\" Do NOT open the door—let the boundary do its job.","by_90_seconds":"Most DEFIANT kids will realize the door won''t open and will wash their hands (often grumbling). When they do, immediately open the door and say: \\\"Routine done! You did it.\\\" Do NOT critique how well they washed.","this_is_success":"Success is NOT perfect hand washing immediately. Success is them completing the routine (even sloppily) WITHOUT a 20-minute power struggle. Over time, the routine becomes automatic because fighting it means they lose access to what they want.","timeline_to_change":"Expect 1-2 weeks of testing. The first 5-7 times, they may test whether the door will really stay closed. Stay calm and consistent. By week 2, most DEFIANT kids start washing automatically because it''s faster than fighting.","dont_expect":["Perfect hand washing with soap for 20 seconds immediately—they may rinse quickly just to get out","Them to stop testing after one successful wash—they will test the boundary multiple times","Cheerful compliance—they may wash their hands but grumble the whole time (that''s still success)","Them to understand germ theory—they''re doing it to regain autonomy, not because they care about germs"]}'::jsonb,

  '[{"scenario":"They scream that they already washed their hands (lie)","response":"Stay calm and factual: \\\"I was here the whole time. The routine wasn''t done. Wash your hands, then the door opens.\\\" Do NOT argue about whether they''re lying—just restate the boundary."},{"scenario":"They wet their hands but skip soap","response":"Point calmly to the soap: \\\"Routine includes soap. Hands, soap, water, dry. Then door opens.\\\" If they refuse, keep door closed and wait. The boundary holds."},{"scenario":"They have a full meltdown, crying and banging on door","response":"Stay calm outside the door. Say once: \\\"I know you''re upset. Wash your hands and you can come out.\\\" Then go silent. Do NOT engage with the tantrum. When they wash (even badly), immediately open the door with no lecture."},{"scenario":"They refuse and sit down in the bathroom, waiting you out","response":"This is rare but possible. Stay calm and wait outside. After 2-3 minutes, say: \\\"When you''re ready to finish the routine, let me know.\\\" Eventually, they will wash because staying in the bathroom is boring. The door stays closed."},{"scenario":"They try to open the door themselves (climbing, unlocking)","response":"If they manage to bypass the lock, calmly implement natural consequence: \\\"You didn''t finish the routine, so no snack/tablet until your hands are clean.\\\" Guide them back to sink. The consequence teaches them that skipping hand washing = losing access to what they want."}]'::jsonb,

  'Calm, mechanical, unmovable. You must be the **bathroom routine system administrator**—not angry about their refusal, not in a power struggle, not explaining germs, just calmly enforcing reality: routine must be completed for door to open. The DEFIANT child needs to feel that hand washing is an immovable system (like a red light), not a rule they can fight to prove their power.',

  ARRAY['hygiene','defiant','hand-washing','bathroom-routine','germs','autonomy','natural-consequences','door-boundary'],
  
  false
);
